          "body": "The chapter opens in the wreckage of David's emotional life. Absalom is dead, the rebellion is over, the battle is won — and the king is weeping, covering his face, crying his son's name in the voice of a man who has lost everything (v. 4). The repetition of the name in verse 4 — 'O my son Absalom, O Absalom, my son, my son!' — is not merely grief; it is a public collapse of royal function. Joab's rebuke in verses 5-7 is the chapter's theological fulcrum. He does not question David's love for Absalom; he questions whether David's private love can be allowed to invert his public obligations. 'You have covered with shame the faces of all your servants, who today have saved your life' (v. 5). The charge is precise: David's mourning has communicated to his army that their loyalty was worth less than the enemy's death. The sons of Zeruiah — Joab and Abishai — are often crude instruments in the Samuel narrative, but here Joab speaks as a genuine prophet of political reality: a king who cannot govern his grief cannot govern his kingdom. David's immediate compliance (v. 8, 'the king arose and sat in the gate') is remarkable — he does not argue with Joab. He accepts the rebuke and returns to his public role. The sitting in the gate is the resumption of the judicial-administrative function of kingship; the gate is where cases are heard and decisions rendered (Ruth 4:1-12; Prov 31:23). The chapter's opening arc moves from paralyzed father to functional king in eight verses — but the damage to the army's morale is not undone so quickly."
